, Warwickshire, England","Leckhampstead, Buckinghamshire, England":"Leckhampstead, Buckinghamshire, England","nameMeanings":[{"name":"de","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Indian Dilip, Anirban, Gopal, Alok, Anindya, Arunava, Asit, Asok, Dibyendu, Goutam, Indra, Indranil.","Indian: variant of   Dey  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Dey","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Indian Ashit, Indu, Naina, Partha, Soumya, Ajit, Anjan, Anjana, Anup, Arjun, Arun, Ashim.","English, Scottish, and Welsh: variant of   Day  .","German: topographic name from a field name in North Rhine-Westphalia, denoting a sizeable piece of land, from Middle Low German <i>dē</i> ‘thigh’ (referring to the shape of the property)."]}]},{"name":"Brereton","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["English: habitational name from any of the places called Brereton, in Cheshire and Staffordshire, and sometimes from Brearton in Yorkshire or Brierton in Durham. Brereton in Staffordshire is named with Old English <i>brǣr</i>, <i>brēr</i> ‘briar’ + Old English <i>dūn</i> ‘hill’ as its final element; the others are named with Old English <i>brǣr</i>, <i>brēr</i> ‘briar’ + <i>tūn</i> ‘enclosure, settlement’."],"variants":[{"name":"Brewerton","meanings":["English: variant of   Brereton  , the result of confusion by folk etymology with the occupational name   Brewer  ."]},{"name":"Brierton","meanings":["English: habitational name from Brierton in County Durham (formerly in Yorkshire) or Brearton in North Yorkshire, which are both named with Old English <i>brēr</i> ‘briar’ + <i>tūn</i> ‘farmstead’, or Brereton in Cheshire, which has the same origin (see   Brereton  )."]}]},{"name":"Alice","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Originally a variant of   Adelaide  , representing an Old French spelling of a reduced form of Germanic <i>Adalheidis</i>. <i>Alice</i> and <i>Adelaide</i> were already regarded as distinct names in English during the medieval period. <i>Alice</i> enjoyed a surge of popularity in the 19th century and periods of favour ever since. It was the name of the central character of  Lewis Carroll's  Alice's Adventures in Wonderland (  1865 ) and Through the Looking Glass (  1872 ), who was based on his child friend  Alice Liddell , daughter of the Dean of Christ Church, Oxford."],"variants":[{"name":"Alys","meanings":["Variant spelling of   Alice ."]},{"name":"Alis","meanings":["equivalent of <b>Alice</b> ."]}]}],"historicEvents":[{"id":1705197,"age":4,"year":"1455","julianDay":2252488,"title":"Wars of the Roses","description":"Wars of the Roses was a series of English civil wars for control of the throne of England between the royal families House of Lancaster and the House of York. The name of the war was derived as the red rose was the symbol of the Lancastrians and the white rose was the symbol of the Yorks.","url":"https://www.history.com/topics/british-history/wars-of-the-roses","urlTitle":"History - Wars of the Roses","jurisdictionLevel":2}],"lifeSummary":"When Alice de Brereton was born on 9 July 1450, in Stratford on Avon, Warwickshire, England, her father, Thomas Brereton, was 36 and her mother, Lydia Ward, was 23. She had at least 1 son and 1 daughter with Sir John Alexander Webb II. She died about 1490, in Stratford on Avon, Warwickshire, England, United Kingdom, at the age of 41."},"et":{"9 July 1450–about 1490":"9. juuli 1450–umbes 1490","1450–1490":"1450–1490","1457–1519":"1457–1519","1459–1490":"1459–1490","1450–1500":"1450–1500","1480–1560":"1480–1560","1483–1516":"1483–1516","1415–1505":"1415–1505","1427–1498":"1427–1498","11 Jan 1483":"11. jaanuar 1483","about 1490":"umbes 1490","1483":"1483","1560":"1560","1450":"1450","1480":"1480","1490":"1490","28 April 1452":"28. aprill 1452","1415":"141